-- Bearing Fruit that Lasts
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus said, "I chose you and appointed you so that you might go and bear fruit—fruit that will last" (John 15:16). Not just activity but lasting impact; not just busyness but eternal significance. Fruit-bearing is the measure of a life well-lived.

In John 15, Jesus uses a vineyard metaphor: He''s the vine, we''re branches, the Father is the gardener. Branches don''t strain to produce fruit—they receive life from the vine. Fruitfulness flows from abiding, not striving. "Apart from me you can do nothing" (15:5). The gardener prunes fruitful branches to increase their yield, explaining why sometimes God''s most productive servants experience painful cutting.

This study examines fruit-bearing: what it is (character and converts), how it happens (abiding in Christ), what hinders it (sin, self-reliance), and what cultivates it (spiritual disciplines). The goal is shifting from activity-based evaluation ("How much am I doing?") to fruit-based evaluation ("What lasting difference is my life making?").'
WHERE slug = 'bearing-fruit-lasts';

-- Bible and End Times
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'End-times teaching generates more heat than light. Charts, timelines, and confident predictions have often proved embarrassing when the predicted dates passed. Yet eschatology (study of last things) is biblical—roughly one-quarter of Scripture concerns future events. The goal is biblical understanding, not sensationalism.

The Bible teaches certain facts about the end: Christ will return visibly, the dead will be raised, final judgment will occur, God will create a new heaven and new earth. Christians disagree about details: timing of rapture, nature of millennium, identity of antichrist. Humility is appropriate where Scripture isn''t definitive.

This study surveys major biblical end-times passages: Daniel''s visions, Jesus'' Olivet Discourse, Paul''s Thessalonian letters, and Revelation. We''ll explain different interpretive approaches without insisting on one system. The focus is on agreed essentials and their implications for how we live now. Eschatology isn''t just future speculation—it shapes present faithfulness.'
WHERE slug = 'bible-end-times';

-- Bible Overview 60 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible is one book with one story: creation, fall, redemption, restoration. From Genesis to Revelation, it traces God''s plan to rescue humanity and renew creation through His Son. Yet most readers struggle to see how 66 books by 40 authors over 1,500 years form a unified whole.

This two-month overview provides the biblical literacy needed to understand any individual passage in its larger context. We''ll trace the main storyline: creation''s goodness, sin''s devastation, Israel''s calling, prophetic anticipation, Christ''s appearing, church''s mission, and consummation''s hope. Along the way, we''ll locate each biblical book within this grand narrative.

By the end, you''ll have a mental map of Scripture. When you read about David, you''ll know where he fits. When Hebrews mentions Melchizedek, you''ll remember his story. When Revelation echoes Ezekiel, you''ll recognize the connection. This big-picture understanding makes all future Bible study more fruitful.'
WHERE slug = 'bible-overview-60';

-- Epistles 30 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The New Testament epistles (letters) comprise 21 of its 27 books—everything from Romans through Jude. Written to churches and individuals facing real challenges, they apply gospel truths to practical life and thereby provide timeless guidance for believers today.

The epistles divide into Pauline (13 letters) and General (8 letters by various authors). They share common features: greeting, thanksgiving, body (teaching and application), and closing. They assume readers know Old Testament background and apostolic teaching, building on foundations laid elsewhere.

This month-long study surveys every epistle, providing context and key themes for each. We''ll read selections from each letter, enough to grasp its message without overwhelming with too much text. By month''s end, you''ll understand what each epistle addresses and be equipped to study any of them more deeply. The epistles aren''t abstract theology but practical guidance for following Jesus in the real world.'
WHERE slug = 'epistles-30-days';

-- Gospels 30 Days (also checking for existing reference)
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The four Gospels—Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John—tell one story from four perspectives. Like four witnesses to an event, they emphasize different details while agreeing on essentials. Together they provide a rich, multidimensional portrait of Jesus Christ.

Matthew wrote for Jewish readers, presenting Jesus as Israel''s promised King. Mark wrote a fast-paced action account, likely for Roman readers, showing Jesus as the Suffering Servant. Luke, the physician, carefully researched and wrote for Gentiles, emphasizing Jesus'' compassion for outsiders. John wrote last, providing theological reflection and unique material, emphasizing Jesus'' deity and eternal life.

This month-long study reads through all four Gospels, highlighting each evangelist''s distinctive contribution. We''ll see Jesus through four sets of eyes, gaining appreciation for the one Lord portrayed in complementary ways. By month''s end, you''ll understand the Gospels'' relationships and be equipped to study Jesus'' life with depth and nuance.'
WHERE slug = 'gospels-30-days';

-- Hope and Final Victory
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Christianity''s hope isn''t wishful thinking but confident expectation based on God''s promises and Christ''s resurrection. Because Jesus rose, we will rise. Because He conquered death, we will conquer death. Because He reigns now, He will reign forever. The outcome is certain; we await its consummation.

This hope isn''t passive escapism. The certainty of Christ''s victory motivates present faithfulness. Paul wrote, "Always give yourselves fully to the work of the Lord, because you know that your labor in the Lord is not in vain" (1 Corinthians 15:58). Our work matters precisely because it contributes to an eternal kingdom.

This study explores Christian hope: its basis (resurrection), its content (what we hope for), its function (how hope sustains), and its final fulfillment (what happens when Christ returns). In an age of despair, anxiety, and uncertainty, believers can possess unshakeable hope—not because circumstances are good but because our God is faithful and His victory is assured.'
WHERE slug = 'hope-final-victory';

-- Key Bible Stories 30 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible isn''t primarily a collection of propositions but a story—God''s story of creating, losing, and redeeming a people for Himself. Within this grand narrative are countless individual stories: creation, flood, exodus, conquest, kingdom, exile, and return; Jesus'' birth, ministry, death, and resurrection; the church''s birth and mission.

Stories teach differently than commands. They show rather than tell, inviting us to see ourselves in the characters, their struggles, their failures, and their victories. Jesus taught primarily through parables—stories that reveal truth to those with ears to hear.

This month-long study walks through 30 key Bible stories in canonical order, showing how each contributes to the overall narrative. We''ll read familiar stories with fresh eyes, seeing connections we''ve missed and applications we''ve overlooked. By month''s end, you''ll have a firm grasp of the biblical storyline and its relevance for your own story.'
WHERE slug = 'key-bible-stories-30';

-- Leadership and Servanthood
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The world''s leadership model is top-down: leaders give orders, followers obey. Jesus inverted this: "The greatest among you should be like the youngest, and the one who rules like the one who serves... I am among you as one who serves" (Luke 22:26-27).

Servant leadership isn''t weakness but strength channeled for others'' benefit. It requires security—knowing your identity doesn''t depend on position or recognition. Jesus could wash feet because "he knew that the Father had put all things under his power" (John 13:3). From that security, He served.

This study examines servant leadership through biblical examples: Moses advocating for rebellious people, David caring for his men, Nehemiah working alongside the builders, Jesus training twelve ordinary men. We''ll apply these principles to various leadership contexts: home, church, workplace, and community. The goal is developing Jesus'' leadership posture: authority exercised through service.'
WHERE slug = 'leadership-servanthood';

-- New Testament 90 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The New Testament records the climax of biblical history: God''s Son entering creation, dying for sins, rising from death, and launching a movement that spans the globe. Its 27 books—Gospels, Acts, Epistles, and Revelation—were written within about 50 years (AD 45-95) by eyewitnesses or their close associates.

Reading the entire New Testament in 90 days requires roughly 10-15 minutes daily—manageable for most schedules. The immersive experience reveals connections that piece-meal reading misses. You''ll see how the Gospels'' story continues in Acts, how the Epistles apply gospel truths, and how Revelation consummates all themes.

This plan reads the New Testament in its traditional order, though not strictly chronologically. Daily readings are sized for consistent progress without overwhelming. By the end of three months, you''ll have encountered Jesus'' life, the church''s birth, apostolic teaching, and apocalyptic hope—the essential story that changed the world.'
WHERE slug = 'new-testament-90';
